Process:
When I receive a brief, I first try to clearly understand the objective, target audience, and expected outcome. I break the brief into key points and identify the main message that needs to be communicated. If anything is unclear, I prefer clarifying it before starting.
Next, I do some quick research for inspiration, trends, and references that align with the theme. I then brainstorm ideas and create a rough concept or outline. For visual content, I think about layout, colors, typography, and overall aesthetics. For written content, I focus on tone, clarity, and engagement.
After creating the first draft, I review it to ensure it matches the brief and effectively communicates the message. I refine the design or content by improving structure, correcting errors, and enhancing visual appeal. Before delivering, I double-check details and make final adjustments. I’m open to feedback and revisions because I believe good content becomes great through refinement and collaboration.
Feedback:
If I receive feedback that my design “doesn’t feel right” without specific details, I would respond calmly and professionally. Instead of taking it personally, I would ask polite follow-up questions to understand what exactly feels off — whether it’s the colors, layout, typography, tone, or overall mood. I believe clarity is important for improvement.
I would request examples or references to better understand their expectations. After gathering clearer input, I would revise the design accordingly and present an improved version. I also like to explain my design choices briefly, so there is mutual understanding.
For me, feedback is part of the creative process. Even unclear feedback is an opportunity to refine the work and align it better with the vision. My focus would always be on improving the final outcome, not defending my design.

Process:
My creative process usually starts by clearly understanding the brief and the goal of the task. I first read the instructions carefully to know what the final outcome should be, who the audience is, and what message needs to be communicated. This helps me get a clear direction before starting the work.
Next, I spend some time thinking and gathering ideas. I may look for inspiration, examples, or references related to the topic so that I can understand what works well. After collecting ideas, I start planning the structure of the content. I create a rough outline or draft to organize my thoughts and make sure the message is clear.
Once the basic idea is ready, I begin creating the actual content. During this stage, I focus on making it simple, engaging, and easy to understand. After completing the first version, I review the work carefully to check for mistakes and improve the quality. I also make small changes to make the content clearer and more effective.
Finally, I make the final adjustments and deliver the content, ensuring that it meets the requirements of the brief and communicates the message properly.
Philosophy:
A good poster should clearly communicate its message and attract attention. Three essential elements of a good poster are:
1. Clear and Simple Message
A good poster should have a clear main idea that people can understand quickly. The message should be short, direct, and easy to read so that viewers can grasp the purpose of the poster within a few seconds.
2. Attractive Visual Design
Visual elements like images, colors, icons, and graphics help make the poster eye-catching. A good design grabs attention and helps explain the message visually. The visuals should be relevant to the topic and not overcrowded.
3. Proper Layout and Readability
The information should be well organized with proper spacing, headings, and readable fonts. Important information such as the title or key points should stand out. A clean layout makes the poster easy to read and understand.
Together, these elements help a poster effectively attract viewers and communicate its message quickly and clearly.
Feedback:
If I receive feedback that my design “doesn’t feel right” without specific details, my first step would be to politely ask for more clarification. I would try to understand what exactly the person feels is missing or unclear. For example, I might ask whether the issue is related to the colors, layout, message, or overall style. This helps me understand the expectations better.
Next, I would review my design carefully and try to see it from the viewer’s perspective. I would check whether the design clearly communicates the message, whether the layout is balanced, and whether the visuals match the purpose of the content.
After that, I would make a few alternative changes or improvements based on the feedback and share them with the team for further suggestions. This allows us to compare options and choose the best version.
I believe feedback is an important part of the creative process. Even if it is not very specific at first, it gives an opportunity to improve the work and create a design that better matches the audience’s expectations and the project’s goals.

Team Failure:
During our college New Year event, I was part of the organizing team and my role was to design the theme and prepare the main display board. I had to print the poster, cut it properly, and paste it neatly on a large cardboard for decoration at the entrance.

While working on it, I made a mistake. I didn’t measure the cardboard correctly before cutting the poster. After pasting, I realized the alignment was slightly tilted and one side had less margin. It didn’t look clean, and since it was the main display, it was noticeable.

At first, I felt stressed because we were already short on time. But instead of leaving it as it was, I told the team about the mistake. I carefully removed the poster, reprinted it, and this time measured everything properly before cutting and pasting. I also asked one teammate to check the alignment before fixing it permanently.

In the end, the final board looked neat and attractive. That situation taught me to double-check measurements and not rush important work.
Crisis Mgmt:
Priority Ranking:

1) Projector fails
2) Keynote speaker cancels
3) 50 more people show up

I would treat the projector failure as the top priority because the event is starting in 30 minutes, and technical issues can stop the entire program. If the projector is not working, presentations, visuals, and even the flow of the event can be affected.

My first action would be to immediately call the technical team and check whether it’s a cable issue, power problem, or device fault. At the same time, I would arrange a backup option like another projector or even a large display screen if available. If no replacement is available, I would quickly inform the speakers to be ready to continue without slides and adjust the program accordingly.

The speaker cancellation would be handled next by rearranging the schedule or assigning another person to fill that slot. Managing extra attendees would be important too, but it can be handled by arranging additional chairs and managing space quickly.

Team Failure:
During my college days, I worked on a group project where we had to prepare and submit a PowerPoint presentation by the next day. We had already divided the work among the team members, and everyone was responsible for completing their assigned part. However, just a day before submission, one of our teammates informed us that he wouldn’t be able to finish his section on time due to some personal reasons.

At first, the team felt stressed because the deadline was very close, and his part was an important section of the presentation. Instead of blaming him or panicking, I decided to focus on finding a solution. I suggested that we quickly review the incomplete section, divide it among the remaining team members, and work together to finish it that same day. I also helped reorganize the slides so that the flow of the presentation would remain clear and consistent.

We coordinated properly, supported each other, and stayed calm while completing the extra work. I took responsibility for compiling all the slides, checking for errors, and ensuring the final presentation looked polished and well-structured. In the end, we successfully completed the presentation and submitted it on time.

This experience taught me the importance of teamwork, staying calm under pressure, and taking initiative when something goes wrong. I learned that problems can be solved more effectively when we focus on solutions instead of blaming others, and that leadership sometimes means stepping up quietly to support the team when it matters most.
Crisis Mgmt:
1) Projector fails
2) 50 more people show up
3) Keynote speaker cancels

Why this order?

1) Projector fails (Highest Priority)
This is an immediate technical issue that can completely stop the event from running as planned. If the projector is needed for presentations, visuals, or the keynote, the event cannot proceed smoothly without it. It affects the entire audience at once.

First Action:
Immediately contact the technical team or venue support to troubleshoot the issue. At the same time, arrange a backup solution — such as another projector, a different room setup, or switching to a no-slides format if necessary. While this is being handled, I would inform the team to keep attendees engaged (music, networking, announcements) to avoid confusion or frustration.

2) 50 more people show up
This is a logistics challenge — seating, materials, and space management must be adjusted quickly. However, it is manageable if the team coordinates properly (adding chairs, adjusting registration, sharing materials digitally).

3) Keynote speaker cancels
While important, this can be handled by adjusting the schedule — replacing the speaker with a panel discussion, a backup speaker, or moving another segment forward. It affects the program but doesn’t physically stop the event from starting.
Cold Outreach:
Yes, I have. When I reached out to someone I didn’t know—a founder of a small tech startup—to explore potential collaboration, I made sure to personalize the email, clearly explain the value for them, and keep it concise. The outcome was positive: the founder responded within a few days, expressing interest in learning more, which eventually led to a brief call and a mutually beneficial partnership.
The key factors that seemed to make a difference were showing that I understood their work, highlighting the specific benefits for them, and keeping the tone professional but approachable. It reinforced that even cold outreach can work well when it’s targeted and thoughtful

Recursion is nothing but the repeating the same thing in itself 
For example: let's say there are two people Raghu and ram , Raghu asks ram that why didn't he eat ,ram replies that he didn't cook the food yet,Raghu asks why didn't he cook till now,ram replies he didn't had the energy to cook,Raghu asks why doesn't he have the energy,ram replies that he didn't eat yet so he doesn't have the energy again raghu asks why didn't he eat then.

This debate of Raghu and ram doesn't end .
Recursion is the same as their conversation but it can be ended when some condition is given and it is called base condition

Explain Simple: The internet is a vast network of computers across the globe. Your phone or tablet serves as your home in this network. When you select a video or game, your device sends a small message to another computer requesting it. This message breaks into many small pieces called packets, similar to envelopes with directions. These packets travel through cables and the air like cars on highways. They stop at helper computers that direct them to their destination. Once all the pieces reach your device, it reassembles them like a puzzle. This process allows you to view the video or website almost instantly. In essence, the internet consists of computers communicating by sending very fast messages.

Explain Simple:
Imagine you have a big chocolate box. Inside that box, there is another smaller chocolate box. And inside that one, there is one more small box. This keeps going.

Now you want to find the last chocolate. So what do you do?

You open the first box.
Then you open the box inside it.
Then you open the next one.
You keep doing the same thing again and again until there are no more boxes left. Then finally, you get the chocolate.

Recursion is like that. It is when a function keeps calling itself to solve a smaller part of the same problem. But it must know when to stop — like stopping when there are no more boxes.

If it doesn’t stop, it will keep opening boxes forever.

Explain Simple:
Recursion means :-
For example:-
when a teacher asks a student to write a sentence 10 times. Instead of thinking about all 10 at once, the student writes the sentence one time and then tells himself to write it 9 more times. After writing it again, he tells himself to write it 8 more times, and this keeps happening. Each time, the task becomes smaller because the number decreases. When the count finally becomes 1, he writes it one last time and stops. That stopping point is called the base condition. So recursion means solving a big task by doing one part of it and then asking yourself to solve the remaining smaller part in the same way until nothing is left to do

Explain Simple:
WHAT ARE APIs:
Think of this like you are in a toy store, and you want a certain toy car from the back room. You don't go get it yourself; you tell the storekeeper exactly what you want, such as "the red race car with shiny wheels." The storekeeper goes to get it, checks if it's okay, and brings it right to you.

APIs Are Like That Storekeeper
APIs are very helpful messengers for computers. When one app (like your game) wants information from another app (like the weather app), it asks the API nicely: "Hey, what's the weather today?" 

How It Works Super Simply
The API goes to the weather app, gets the sunny or rainy stuff, and brings it right back fast—without the two apps ever meeting in person. It's like magic notes that help phone games, maps, and videos all work together nicely!
